{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cf7e531c-6dda-443f-9aeb-7f314624d298","content":"\n\nRun **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the **same versions** already recorded. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but won't pull newer workload packages to match a newer SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK changed → `dotnet workload update`. Installation broken/corrupt → `dotnet workload repair`.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, try a clean + restore:\n```bash\ndotnet clean && dotnet restore\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c4709cd3-2e5e-474b-a35a-ac8526913282","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":250},"id":"f498a465-3950-46a0-b495-590f787ff909","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:52:12.178Z","parentId":"792917da-9f92-4f70-8c43-0af05f37f5ad"}
